'''David Lloyd Johnston''' {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Canada|CC]] [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|CMM]] [[Order of Merit of the Police Forces|COM]]}} (born June 28, 1941)<ref name=CV1>{{citation| last=Johnston| first=David| title=Curriculum Vitae| date=December 2008| page=1| publisher=University of Waterloo| accessdate=July 8, 2010| ref=CITEREF_Johnston_2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| editor-last=Redmond| editor-first=Chris| title=The first day of the rest of your life| journal=Daily Bulletin| publisher=University of Waterloo| location=Waterloo| date=June 28, 2006| url=http://www.bulletin.uwaterloo.ca/2006/jun/28we.html| accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> is a [[Canada|Canadian]] academic, author and statesman. He is the current [[Governor General of Canada]], the [[List of Governors General of Canada#Governors General of Canada, 1867-present|28th]] since [[Canadian Confederation]].

Johnston was born and raised in [[Ontario]], studying there before enrolling at [[Harvard University]] and later [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] and [[Queen's University|Queen's]] Universities. He then went on to work as a professor at various post-secondary institutions in Canada, eventually serving administrative roles as dean of law at the [[University of Western Ontario]], principal of [[McGill University]], and president of the [[University of Waterloo]]. At the same time, Johnston involved himself with politics and public service, moderating political debates and chairing commissions in both the federal and provincial spheres, his most renowned position in that field being the chairmanship of the inquiry into the [[Airbus affair]]. He was in 2010 appointed as governor general by [[Elizabeth II]], [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen of Canada]], on the recommendation of [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Stephen Harper]], to replace [[Micha<U+00EB>lle Jean]] as viceroy. At the time, Johnston was predominantly praised as a worthy choice for the Queen's representative, though his appointment was denounced by Quebec sovereigntists.

As governor general, Johnston is entitled to be styled ''[[Excellency#Commonwealth usage|His Excellency]]'' while in office and ''[[The Right Honourable]]'' for the duration of his viceregal tenure and life beyond. Given current practice, he will be sworn into the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]] when his term as the Queen's representative ends.

==Early life and education==
Johnston was born in [[Greater Sudbury|Sudbury]], [[Ontario]], to Lloyd Johnston, the owner of a [[hardware store]],<ref name=Akin>{{Citation| last=Akin| first=David| title=David Johnston Canada's next GG <U+2014> Attended high school in Sault| newspaper=Sault Star| date=July 9, 2010| url=http://www.saultstar.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=2659482| accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> and Dorothy Stonehouse. He attended [[Sault Collegiate Institute]] in nearby [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Sault Ste. Marie]] before moving on to [[Harvard University]] in 1959,<ref name=Record>{{Citation| last=Aggerholm| first=Barbara| last2=Kwawada| first2=Karen| title=No stranger to glare of politics| newspaper=The Record| date=November 16, 2007| url=http://news.therecord.com/article/270332| accessdate=August 6, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=The International Who's Who 2004| publisher=Europa Publications| page=826| isbn=9781857435108}}</ref> earning his [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree, ''[[Latin honors#History of usage in the United States|magna cum laude]]'', from there in 1963.<ref name=CV1 /> While at Harvard, under the coaching of [[Cooney Weiland]], Johnston [[Captain (ice hockey)|captained]] the [[Harvard Crimson|varsity]] [[ice hockey]] team, was twice selected to the [[All-America]] team,<ref name=GM>{{Citation| last=Galloway| first=Gloria| last2=Ibbitson| first2=John| title=Next governor-general unveiled| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=July 8, 2010| url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/next-governor-general-unveiled/article1632781/| accessdate=July 10, 2010}}</ref> and met and befriended [[Erich Segal]],<ref>{{Citation| last=Brennan| first=Richard J.| title=Academic, athletic David Johnston next Gov. Gen.| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=July 8, 2010| url=http://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/833556--academic-athletic-david-johnston-next-gov-gen| accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> the two becoming jogging partners.<ref name=Record /> In 1970, Segal wrote the best-selling novel ''[[Love Story (novel)|Love Story]]'', basing a character in the book{{mdash}} Davey, a captain of the hockey team{{mdash}} on Johnston.<ref name=Akin /><ref name=GM />

Johnston later attended the [[University of Cambridge]], obtaining a [[Bachelor of Laws]] with honours in 1965, and another with first class honours from [[Queen's University]] in 1966.<ref name=CV1 /> During that period, Johnston married his high school sweetheart,<ref name=cbcbio>{{Cite news| title=David Johnston: Lawyer, academic, Canada's next GG| publisher=CBC| date=July 8, 2010| url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2010/07/08/f-governor-general-david-johnston-profile.html| accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> [[Sharon Johnston|Sharon]],<ref name=Akin /><ref>{{Cite press release| title=David Johnston named UW president| publisher=University of Waterloo| date=October 7, 1998| url=http://newsrelease.uwaterloo.ca/news.php?id=1068| accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> with whom he had five daughters.<ref name=CV1 /><ref name=Akin />

==Academic career==
Johnston has had a long academic career, during which he came to specialise in [[securities regulation]], [[corporation law]], [[public policy]] and [[information technology law]].<ref name=CV1 /> After 1966, he worked for two years as an assistant professor at the [[Queen's University Faculty of Law]] and then joined the [[University of Toronto Faculty of Law|University of Toronto's law faculty]], where he taught until 1974, eventually being promoted to the rank of full professor. Johnston was then appointed as dean of the [[Western Law School|University of Western Ontario Law School]], serving between 1974 and 1979, at which time he was elevated to become the fourteenth Principal and Vice-Chancellor of [[McGill University]]. It was during his time in that role that he became acquainted with [[Pierre Trudeau|Pierre]] and [[Margaret Trudeau]], as the Johnston children played with [[Pierre Trudeau#Marriage and children|the Trudeau children]] when the families were at their respective, adjacent cottages in the [[Laurentian Mountains|Laurentians]].<ref name=Record />
[[File:David Johnston introducing Justin Trudeau at Waterloo.jpg|thumb|left|Johnston, then President of the [[University of Waterloo]], introducing [[Justin Trudeau]] as a speaker at the university, March, 2006]]

Johnston stepped down in 1994 as principal of McGill to remain at the university only as a law professor until he was in 1999 installed as the fifth President of the [[University of Waterloo]]. At that time, the couple acquired a home in [[Wellesley, Ontario|Heidelberg]], Ontario,<ref name=SSF2>{{Citation| title=Lee Myers assumes Chair of Festival's Board of Governors| publisher=Stratford Shakespeare Festival| page=2| date=March 22, 2010| url=http://www.stratfordfestival.ca/uploadedfiles/stratford/media/2010_press_releases/pressreleaseboardchair2010.pdf?n=1408| accessdate=August 6, 2010| ref=CITEREF_Stratford_Shakespeare_Festival_2010}}</ref> and began operating an adjacent horse training ranch, ''Chatterbox Farm''.<ref>{{Citation| last=Morrow| first=Adrian | title=Affable governor-general designate enjoys a town and country life| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=July 10, 2010| url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/affable-governor-general-designate-enjoys-a-town-and-country-life/article1635476/| accessdate=August 6, 2010}}</ref>

==Boards, commissions, and media==
Johnston  has moderated several televised [[Canadian leaders debates|leaders' debates]],<ref name=CV9>{{Harvnb| Johnston| 2008| p=9}}</ref> the first being between [[Pierre Trudeau]], [[Joe Clark]], and [[Ed Broadbent]], prior to [[Canadian federal election, 1979|the 1979 federal election]], and he returned five years later to play the same role before the [[Canadian federal election, 1984|election of 1984]], in a debate featuring [[Brian Mulroney]], [[John Napier Turner|John Turner]], and Broadbent. He also moderated the provincial leaders' debate featuring [[David Peterson]], [[Bob Rae]], and [[Larry Grossman]], in the run up to the [[Ontario general election, 1987|Ontario general election in 1987]].<ref>{{Citation| last=Delacourt| first=Susan| title=Johnston 'believes in nobility of public life'| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=November 15, 2007| url=http://www.thestar.com/news/article/276701| accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> Johnston has also acted as moderator of two public affairs panel discussion programmes, ''The Editors'' and ''The World in Review'', which aired in the 1990s on both [[CBC Newsworld]] in Canada and [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] in the [[United States]].<ref name=CV9 />

Investigations commissioned by both federal and provincial [[Queen-in-Council|Crowns-in-Council]] have been chaired by Johnston, starting with the [[National Round Table on the Environment and the Economy]] in the late 1980s,<ref name=mul>{{Cite news| title=PM taps university president as Mulroney inquiry adviser| publisher=CBC| date=November 14, 2007| url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2007/11/14/johsnton-named.html| accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> followed by the National Task Force on High Speed Broadband Access, the Committee on Information Systems for the Environment, the Advisory Committee on Online Learning, Ontario's Infertility and Adoption Review Panel between 2008 and 2009, and other scientific or public policy panels.<ref name=CV6-8>{{Harvnb| Johnston| 2008| pp=6-8}}</ref> He also sat on the Ontario government's Task Force on Management of Large Scale Information and Information Technology Projects and an Ontario Ministry of Health panel investigating "smart systems." Johnston further served on various corporate [[board of directors|boards of directors]], including those of [[Fairfax Financial Holdings]], [[CGI]], Dominion Textiles, [[Southam Incorporated]], [[SPAR Aerospace]], [[Seagram's]], and [[Canada Trust]], among others,<ref name=CV6-8 /> and on March 22, 2010, was named to the Board of Governors of the [[Stratford Shakespeare Festival]].<ref>{{Harvnb| Stratford Shakespeare Festival| 2010| p=1}}</ref> He is the only non-American citizen to chair the [[Harvard Board of Overseers]].<ref name=SSF2 />

On November 14, 2007, Johnston was appointed by [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[Micha<U+00EB>lle Jean]], on the [[Advice (constitutional)|advice]] of [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Stephen Harper]], as an independent adviser and charged with drafting for the [[Canadian Cabinet|Cabinet]] the terms of reference for the [[public inquiry]], known as the Oliphant Commission, into the [[Airbus affair]].<ref name=mul /> This appointment itself, however, was criticized by the independent citizens' group [[Democracy Watch (Canada)|Democracy Watch]] as a conflict of interest, given that Johnston had once reported directly to Mulroney during the latter's time as prime minister.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Harper's relationship with Mulroney to be reviewed - again| publisher=CanWest| date=July 27, 2008| url=http://www.canada.com/topics/news/story.html?id=96feaae8-bdb9-4690-860d-c68565f2cf0d| accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> Johnston completed his report on January 11, 2008, listing seventeen questions of interest for further investigation.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Mulroney-Schreiber report won<U+2019>t show us the money, critics say |publisher= Globe & Mail| date=May 3, 2010|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/mulroney-schreiber-report-wont-show-us-the-money-critics-say/article1586065/| accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> He did not, however, include as a subject the awarding of the [[Airbus]] contract, on the basis that this aspect had already been investigated by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], prompting criticism from opposition [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]] and accusations that Johnston had acted as the Prime Minister's man.<ref>{{Citation| last=Whittington| first=Les| last2=Brennan| first2=Richard| title=Vague Mulroney probe angers MPs| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=January 12, 2008| url=http://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/293377| accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> This intensified after it was later revealed that Mulroney had accepted $300,000 in cash from [[Karlheinz Schreiber]], but Oliphant could not examine any possible link between that payment and Airbus due to the narrow scope of the commission's mandate.<ref>{{Citation| last=Travers| first=James| title=Mulroney inquiry link could hinder GG contender David Johnston's hopes| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=June 3, 2010| url=http://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/818273--travers-mulroney-inquiry-link-could-hinder-gg-contender-david-johnston-s-hopes| accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> Others, though, such as Peter George, then-president of [[McMaster University]],<ref>{{Citation| last=Ibbitson| first=John| author-link=John Ibbitson| title=University of Waterloo president may have the viceregal touch| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=June 29, 2010| url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/john-ibbitson/university-of-waterloo-president-may-have-the-viceregal-touch/article1623663/| accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> and subsequently the editorial board of ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'',<ref name=GMEd>{{Citation| title=David Johnston: a worthy viceroy| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=July 9, 2010| url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/opinions/editorials/david-johnston-a-worthy-viceroy/article1633550/| accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> as well as [[Andrew Coyne]] in ''[[Maclean's]]'',<ref name=Coyne>{{Cite journal| last=Coyne| first=Andrew| authorlink=Andrew Coyne| title=The Best of Canada Indeed| journal=Maclean's| issue=July 2010| publisher=Rogers Communications| location=Toronto| date=July 8, 2010| url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2010/07/08/the-best-of-canada-indeed/| issn=0024-9262| accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> defended Johnston, detailing his integrity and independence. Johnston's role as special adviser was parodied by [[Roger Abbott]] on the January 11, 2008, airing of [[Air Farce Live]].<ref>{{Cite episode| title=Episode 15-10| url=http://www.airfarce.com/seasons/season15/080111.html| series=Royal Canadian Air Farce| serieslink=Air Farce Live | network=CBC| city=Toronto| airdate=January 11, 2008| season=15| number=10}}</ref>

For this corporate, government, charitable, and academic work, Johnston was in 1994 appointed to the [[Order of Canada]] as an Officer; he was promoted within the order to the rank of Companion in 1997.<ref name=OC>{{Canadian honour |Type=CC| ID=3770| accessdate=June 25, 2010}}</ref> Johnston also gained a reputation as a non-partisan individual,<ref name=Akin /><ref name=Hebert>{{Citation| last=H<U+00E9>bert| first=Chantal| author-link=Chantal H<U+00E9>bert| title=Johnston appointment ends rock star era at Rideau Hall| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=July 9, 2010| url=http://mobile.thestar.com/mobile/canada/article/833717| accessdate=July 9, 2010}}</ref> but has expressed explicit support for [[Canadian federalism]], having written a book opposing [[Quebec sovereignty movement|Quebec separatism]], ''If Quebec Goes: The Real Cost of Separation'',<ref name=Que>{{Citation| last=Anderson| first=Kalli| title='Federalist extremist' heads for Rideau Hall| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=July 15, 2010| url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/federalist-extremist-heads-for-rideau-hall/article1640968/| accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> He has also published numerous books on law, chapters in other volumes, magazine articles, and aided in writing legislation.<ref>{{Harvnb| Johnston| 2008| pp=2-6}}</ref> and sat as the co-chair of the Montreal No Committee during the [[Quebec independence referendum, 1995|1995 Quebec referendum on independence]].<ref name=Hebert /><ref name=Que />

==Governor generalship==
On July 8, 2010 the [[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|Office of the Prime Minister of Canada]] announced that Queen [[Elizabeth II]] had approved Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]]'s choice of Johnston to succeed Micha<U+00EB>lle Jean as the [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen's]] representative. At the time, Harper said of Johnston that he represents "the best of Canada, he represents hard work, dedication, public service and humility. I am confident he will continue to embody these traits in his new role as the Crown representative in Canada."<ref name=Appt>{{Citation| last=Brennan| first=Richard J.| title=Academic David Johnston Canada's next Gov. Gen.| newspaper=Toronto Star| date=July 8, 2010| url=http://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/833556--academic-david-johnston-canada-s-next-gov-gen?bn=1| accessdate=July 11, 2010}}</ref><ref name=PMO>{{cite web| url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?category=1&id=3536&featureId=6&pageId=26| last=Office of the Prime Minister of Canada| auhtorlink=Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)| title=PM welcomes appointment of David Johnston as Governor General Designate (Media Release)| date=July 8, 2010| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref> Johnston himself said in a press conference that he and his wife had always been dedicated to service and vowed to, while in office, defend Canadian heritage and institutions.<ref name=GM /><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.ctvbc.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100708/new-gg-david-johnston-100708/20100708?hub=BritishColumbiaHome| title=Incoming governor general proud to serve Canadians| publisher=CTV| date=July 8, 2010| accessdate=July 8, 2010}}</ref>

A special search committee convened by the Prime Minister recommended Johnston for the viceregal position; the group was headed by Sheila-Marie Cook, [[Secretary to the Governor General of Canada|secretary to the Governor General]],<ref name=PMOrelease>{{cite web| url=http://news.gc.ca/web/article-eng.do?m=/index&nid=546739| last=Office of the Prime Minister of Canada| authorlink=Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)| title=Governor General Consultation Committee| date=12 July 2010| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> and further consisted of [[Kevin MacLeod]],<ref name=GM /> the [[Canadian Secretary to the Queen]], [[Usher of the Black Rod of the Senate of Canada]], and parliament's top protocol officer; [[Christopher Manfredi]], dean of the Faculty of Arts at McGill University; [[Rainer Knopff]], a political scientist at the University of Calgary; Father Jacques Monet, of the Canadian Institute of Jesuit Studies; and [[Christopher McCreery]], historian and private secretary to the [[Lieutenant Governor of Nova Scotia]].<ref name=GMEd /><ref>{{Citation| last=Curry| first=Bill| title=Selection panel ordered to find non-partisan governor-general: PMO| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=11 July 2010| url=http://m.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/selection-panel-ordered-to-find-non-partisan-governor-general-pmo/article1636004/?service=mobile| accessdate=11 July 2010}}</ref> The committee conducted extensive national consultations with over 200 people including academics, sitting and retired political leaders of all political persuasions including provincial premiers, current and former political party leaders, former prime ministers and others in order to develop a short list of candidates for the position.<ref name=PMO /><ref name=PMOrelease/><ref name=globe9>{{cite web |url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/opinions/editorials/david-johnston-a-worthy-viceroy/article1633550/ |title=David Johnston: a worthy viceroy |work=''Globe and Mail'' |date=July 9, 2010}}</ref> Also on the short list were other distinguished Canadians including [[John de Chastelain]] and [[John Fraser (journalist)|John Fraser]].<ref name=globe9/>

The appointment was widely praised, its announcement garnering positive words from individuals like former University of Toronto president [[Robert Prichard]] and columnist Andrew Coyne.<ref name=Coyne /><ref name=corners>{{Citation| last=Ibbitson| first=John| author-link=John Ibbitson| last2=Curry| first2=Bill| last3=Taber| first3=Jane| last4=Church| first4=Elizabeth | title=Legal scholar, creative administrator <U+2013> and he's good in the corners| newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=July 8, 2010| url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/legal-scholar-creative-administrator-and-hes-good-in-the-corners/article1633695/| accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> [[Leader of the Opposition (Canada)|Opposition Leader]] [[Michael Ignatieff]] stated, "David Johnston<U+2019>s dedication to learning and innovation... combined with his legal expertise and constitutional knowledge makes him an ideal choice for Governor General."<ref>{{Cite press release| title=Statement from Liberal leader Michael Ignatieff on Governor General Designate David Johnston| publisher=Liberal Party of Canada| date=July 8, 2010| url=http://www.liberal.ca/en/newsroom/media-releases/18478_statement-from-liberal-leader-michael-ignatieff-on-governor-general-designate-david-johnston| accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> The president of [[Quebec]]'s ''Conseil de la souverainet<U+00E9>'', G<U+00E9>rald Larose, however, declared Johnston to be an "adversary" of [[Quebec sovereignty movement|Quebec independence]] and Mario Beaulieu, head of the [[Saint-Jean-Baptiste Society]], called the nomination of Johnston "partisan" and the governor general-designate himself a "federalist extremist."<ref name=Que /> Columnists also speculated that Johnston would likely face difficult constitutional choices, given the probability that the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian parliament's]] minority status would continue well after the start of his tenure as viceroy.<ref name=VanSun>{{Citation| last=Kennedy| first=Mark| title=A constitutional crisis likely looms for Canada's next governor general| newspaper=Vancouver Sun| date=September 28, 2010| url=http://www.vancouversun.com/news/constitutional+crisis+likely+looms+Canada+next+governor+general/3592493/story.html| accessdate=September 30, 2010}}</ref>

The Queen issued on September 3, 2010, under the [[royal sign-manual]] and [[Great Seal of Canada]], her commission naming Johnston as her next Canadian representative and,<ref>{{Citation| last=Elizabeth II| author-link=Elizabeth II| publication-date=September 3, 2010| contribution=Proclamation Announcing the Appointment of the Governor General| contribution-url=http://www.gazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2010/2010-10-01-x1/html/extra1-eng.html| periodical=Canada Gazette| volume=144| issue=1| place=Ottawa| publication-place=Ottawa| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=October 1, 2010}}</ref> three days later, Johnston attended an [[Audience (meeting)|audience]] with the Queen during a two day stay at [[Balmoral Castle]]. At that time he was invested by the monarch as a Commander of both the [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|Order of Military Merit]] and [[Order of Merit of the Police Forces]].<ref name=visit>{{Cite news| title=GG-designate visits Queen| publisher=CBC| date=September 5, 2010| url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2010/09/05/gg-designate-meets-queen.html| accessdate=September 5, 2010}}</ref> Johnston then announced to the media that there would be a theme to his installation ceremony: A call to service; he elaborated: "This theme of service echoes that of Her Majesty the Queen's 2010 visit 'Honouring the Canadian Record of Service{{mdash}} Past, Present and Future,' and illustrates how the governor general exemplifies the Canadian value of service to community and country."<ref name=VanSun /> The ceremony took place on [[Parliament Hill]], in [[Ottawa]], on October&nbsp;1, 2010;<ref name=swear-in>{{citation | title = GG David Johnston officially sworn in | url = http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2010/10/01/governor-general-david-johnston-ceremony.html | publisher = CBC News | date = 1 October 2010}}.</ref> Johnston recited and signed the oaths of office in the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]], before an audience that included the nine judges of the [[Supreme Court of Canada|Supreme Court]], Prime Minister Harper, and former prime ministers and governors general,<ref name=swear-in /> including Micha<U+00EB>lle Jean. He then gave a fifteen minute address.

==Titles, styles, honours, and arms==
===Titles===
{{Infobox viceroy styles
| image    = [[File:Crest of the Governor-General of Canada.svg|50px]]
| name     = David Lloyd Johnston<br>(2010-present)
| dipstyle = His Excellency the Right Honourable<br>''Son Excellence le tr<U+00E8>s honorable''
| offstyle = Your Excellency<br>''Votre Excellence''
| altstyle = Sir<br>''Monsieur''
}}
* '''June 28, 1941{{ndash}} October 1, 2010''': ''Mister/Monsieur'' David Lloyd Johnston
* '''October 1, 2010{{ndash}}''': ''His Excellency the Right Honourable/Son Excellence le Tr<U+00E8>s Honorable'' David Lloyd Johnston, Governor General and Commander-in-Chief in and over Canada

The Governor General's style and title in full is, in [[English language|English]]: ''His Excellency The Right Honourable David Lloyd Johnston, Chancellor and Principal Companion of the Order of Canada, Chancellor and Commander of the Order of Military Merit, Chancellor and Commander of the Order of Merit of the Police Forces, Governor General and [[Commander-in-Chief of the Canadian Forces|Commander-in-Chief in and over Canada]]'', and in [[French language|French]]: ''Son Excellence le tr<U+00E8>s honorable David Lloyd Johnston, chancelier et compagnon principal de l'ordre du Canada, chancelier et commandant de l'ordre du m<U+00E9>rite militaire, chancelier et commandant de l'ordre du m<U+00E9>rite des forces de police, gouverneur g<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>ral et commandant en chef du Canada''.

